{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_paperflower_ver01/data/sn92070146/0041418859A/1930121501/1102.xml":{"full_text":"4\nPublished by\nIMPERIAL VALLEY\nPRESS, ino.\nW. C. COSTELLO,\nManager\nTHE RISE OF THE RACKET\nThe word \u201cracket\u201d is a peculiar and\nunlovely contribution of modern Amer\nica to current English. It is in wide use\njust now, and everyone knows what it\nmeans. But few people realize the\namazing and dismaying extent to which\nthe racket has flourished of late in b\u2019g\ncities. _\nDistrict Attorney rain <>l New 1 ork\nrecently began an investigation otto\nrackets in that city. He emerged from\nit the other day with the disgusted re\nmark that \u201cthere's a racket in everything\nfrom babies' milk to funeral coaches,\nand to list a few of the more obnoxious\nrackets.\nFor example: the district attorney is\ntold that every ton of freight that ar\nrives in New \\ork must pay its toll to\nsome racketeer. Every professional mu\nsician has to pay a dollar a night to some\nother racketeer; if he does not, his in\nstrument will be smashed. Dry cleaners\nand laundries contribute millions of dol\nlars a year; if they refuse, their delivery\nwagons are wrecked, their drivers are\nslugged or acid is smuggled into their\nshops and poured on the customers\nclothing. Other racketeers have organ\nized \u201cprotective associations lor mer\nchants, promising each subscriber that\nwatchmen will look out for his store at\nnight; if a merchant refuses to enter, his\nstore windows are smashed.\nAnd so it goes. That paragraph lists\nonlv a few of the rackets that afflict, not\nonly New York and Chicago, but every\nother large city and many smaller ones.\nThe spectacle is dismaying beyond\nwords. As long as the racketeer thrives,\nthe ordinary guarantees of peace and\norder supposed to exist in a civilized\nstate are utterly worthless. The rac\nketeer svmbolizes invisible government\nat its worst. He simply cannot be toler\nated if American civilization is to sur\nvive.\nIt is hardly an exaggeration to say that\ncivic authorities have no problems more\npressing than the problem of the rac\nketeer. If they fail to solve it the entire\nnation, sooner or later, will be in for\nvery serious trouble.\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC STARTS\nFUND TO AID IDLE WORKERS\nBv GEORGE O. CRISSEY\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nSAN FRANCISCO, Dec. 15. <U.R)\n.\u2014There was rejoicing in the homes\nof many unemployed today when i\nit was learned that a loan fund\nwas being raised to relieve the dis\ntress of Southern Pacific workers\nnow on the suspended list as a\nresult of business conditions.\nThe management of the railroad\nand employees who are receiving\nregular salaries are cooperating in\nforming a special fund from which\nthose who were laid off may borrow\nwithout interest.\nEach employee has been to.d he\nmay contribute one per cent of his\nsalary to the fund. Each dollar\nthus raised will be matched by the\nrailroad management. The money\nis to be repaid when the circum-\nstance of the borrower permits.\nThe plan becomes effective Jan\nuary 1 and will continue lor six\nmonths or until the need for aid\nno longer exists.\nMen who were in the Southern\nPacific service for one year or long\ner before being laid oil may apply\nOUT OUR WAY\nTA\nLA\niT'o\nHimE\nTA\n'Jou HOKJTIVJ\nGEl\u2019TiVl' ALUIM\nAmo ME. HA^/iM\n-f CARRV WOU j<7\nAIL_TH\u2018 WAV\nl-lOMC. V\n\nV l\u00ab\n.1, It 1\nW\nV\nw.\n/JT r rTJ\n/^V\n\nL >1) i\u2014\u25a0 i\n\nH\n;j ?j,'\u00abv:\n;<ssk -rr.--'\nm\nm\nm\nf r r-A\nIf\n5\",\nv-\\'\nW^'\nm\n\nL_\nm\nr\n\nme u r*T. off.\nV\\HW MOfAtRS CiET'GrRAV.\nO'-RWILUAMe,\n01630 OY HLA ilHv\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nMonth (By Mail) 5 -50\nSix Months (By Mail) 2.50\nYear (By Mail) 6OO\nt\u2014\u25a0\nfor and receive loans. Money in the\nfund, together with repaid loans,\nwill be returned pro rata to the\ncontributors after the fund is no\nlonger needed.\nLocal offices of the Southern Pa\ncific refused to comment on the\nloan plan but the United Press was\ngiven a circular describing the\nplan in detail, by a Southern Pa\ncific employee. Paul Shoup, pres\nident of the railroad, issued the cir\ncular which said the fund had re\nceived the unanimous approval of\nthe company's officers.\nContributions by employees are\nvoluntary\u2019, although all are urged\nto participate. A central board of\ntrustees will direct the relief work,\naided by committees in each divis\nion in the Southern Pacific system.\nThe circular stresses the point\nthat no one eligible need hesitate\nin applying for aid. It also point\ned out that families of men re\nceiving loan may obtain free med\nical treatment from the railroad\u2019s\nhospital department.\nIt is expected the fund will total\nseveral hundred thousand dollars.\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS, EL CENTttO CALIFORNIA, DEmiOER 15^1030\nTOYS FOR GROW X-UPS\nThe approach of Christmas once more\nbrings us up to that ancient question:\nWhose eye is really caught by the store's\ndisplay of Christmas toys\u2014the small\nboy\u2019s or the small boy\u2019s father\u2019s?\nThe small boy. of course, goes for the\ntoy displays in a big way, and lingers\nfondly in front of the windows, feasting\nn>s eyes on the array of trains, automo\nbiles, steel building sets, blocks, games\nand all the rest. But it is his dad who\nreally is smitten to the heart by these\nthings. It is his dad who picks them, out\nfor him (and has a swell time doing it.\ntoo) and it is. very often, his dad who\ngets the most fun out of playing with\nthem on Christmas day.\nIndeed, that is probably one reason\nwhy the father of a family gets such a\nkick out of Christmas. It is the one day\nin all the year when he can get down on\nthe floor, unabashed, and play with toys.\nThe desire to do so is ever-present, li\nthe truth were known, the vast majority\nof staid, dignified and sober men of mid\ndle age would enjoy nothing more than\nthe privilege of spending a few hours ev\nery week fooling around with their sons'\ntovs. But in most cases they can\u2019t do it.\nThey don\u2019t dare to. They can\u2019t help\nthinking that they would look foolish.\nOn Christmas, however, things are dit\nferent. That sort of behavior is more or\nless expected of a man. When all the\npresents have been opened, and the tloor\nis all strewn with tissue paper, ribbons\nand tinsel, then the head of the family\ncan sprawl out on the floor, fit sonny s\nnew train together, and have the time of\nhis life running it about the room. He\ncan take all of those attractive gadgets\nthat he has bought for the boy and play\nwith them himself. Nobody thinks any\nthing of it. Nobody suggests that his\ndignity has suffered.\nSo it is that on Christmas you will find\nall sorts of men squatting on the floor,\npretending that they are children again\nand wishing most heartily that they\nreallv were. And that, perhaps, is one\nof the nicest things about the holiday.\nWe can shed our years, for a few hours.\nWe can get back, briefly, to boyhood\u2014\nand oh, how we love it.\nThe Southern Pacific operates\nthroughout the west and southwest,\nemploying thousands of men. It\n1 also has a fleet of steamboats and\noperates an extensive ferry system\non San Francisco bay.\nBusiness leaders here assumed\nthe six months period during which\nthe fund will be active means that\nexecutives of the railroad anticipate\na business revival within six months\nand estimate that most of the men\nlaid off during 1930 will be back\non the pavroll by the,middle of\n1931.\nI\nTHE WEATHER I\n\nLos Angeles and Vicinity \u2014Fair to\nnight and Tuesday, with moderat\ntemperature; gentle to moderat\nnortheasterly winds.\nSouthern California \u2014Fair tonight\nand Tuesday; no change in tem\nperature; gentle to moderate\u2019north\neast winds.\nLOCAL WEATHER\nRECORDED BV F. A. BAUGHMAN\nL'. S. Weather Bureau\nTempt ratures\nMinimum this morning 3tJ\nMaximum yesterday T 2\nrj o\nIssued Dtily, Except\nSundays. Entered at the\nPost Office, El Centro,\nCalif., as Second-Class\nMatter.\nBY WILLIAMS\n<k.\n-T\nTv\n\nf\nn\nu\n\n'V\nOS?\nS\niJC\u00bb\nFOR\nF.cSTOP\n\n\n\n\nf>\nS\u00a3\n\u25a0-3^\nft\n\n\u00a3X:>\nSi'AAy.vi y\"\nt 1 lAEBBEVOUD\nv 2 j SE tTER BERVEL\nJL '-l OTE COURSE AT\n1\n\n\n\nA time, BErORE\nVOU SPIU- IT\nALE/\n\nx\ny\nV\n51\n1\np\ni\n\nj\nft\n,\\y\n\nv\u00ae-\nL\ni\ni.X\n\nK\nV/o\nBed-Time Stories;\nBy HOWARD E. GARRIS\nCopyright, 1928, by McClure\nNewspaper Syndicate\nUNCLE WIGGILY\u2019S PINCHING\nDOLL\nUnder his bed Uncle Wiggily had\nhidden a large cloth bag. None of\nthe forty sixteen bunny children of\nthe old gentleman rabbit was per\nmitted to so much as open Uncle\nWiggily's door to look under the bed\nat the bag. It was very secret.\nOf course Nurse Jane Fuzzy Wuz\nzy. the muskrat lady housekeeper,\nand Mrs. Longears. who was Uncle\nWiggily\u2019s wife, were permitted to\nlook at the bag under the bed. For\nthey wouldn't tell.\nNow the reason Uncle Wiggily\nkept this bag so secret was that it\nheld Christmas presents. Because\nhe had so many rabbit children and\nbecause Santa Claus was going to\nbe very busy. Uncle Wiggily decided\nto help get the Christmas presents\nahead of time. So the bag under\nthe bed held many jolly Christmas\npresent toys.\nOne morning Uncle Wiggily did\nnot hop out of bed early as he near\nly always did to go adventuring. He\nheard the bunny children slide down\nthe banister rail to get their break\nfast, and he heard them shout:\n\u201cSoon it will be Christmas! Soor.\nit will be Christmas!\"\nThen Uncle Wiggily turned over\nand went to sleep again.\n\u201cMy goodness! Aren\u2019t you up\nyet?\" asked Nurse Jane Fuzzy Wuz\nzy in surprise as she hopped into\nUncle Wiggily\u2019s icom to make up\nthe bed. But of course, she couldn\u2019t\ndo that with him in it.\n\u201cNo, I'm not up yet,\" answered\nMr. Longears. \"I thought I would\nwait until my forty sixteen little\nrabbits hopped off to school Then\nthey won\u2019t tease me to ask what\u2019s\nir the bag under my bed. For some\nof the little tykes must have seen\nit there. So I'll keep out of their\nway.\"\n\u201cWell, then you may get up!\u201d\nsqueaked Nurse Jane with a laugh, j\n\"For all the children have gone to j\nschool.\u201d\n\u201cHas Baby Bunty gone?\"\u2019 asked j\nMr. Longears, opening one eye.\n\u201cThat cute little orphan rabbit\nchild can ask more questions than\nall the others put together. Has\nshe gone to school?\u201d\n\u201cYes, Baby Bunty has gone,\" said\nNurse Jane. \u201cShe hopped away'\nsinging about wishing she would get!\na doll for Christmas.\u201d\n\u201cI hope she gets her wish!\u201d)\nchuckled the rabbit gentleman.:\nWell, 1 11 get up soon, Nurse Jane,\u201d\nand with that he turned over and\nwent to sleep again.\n\"Dear me!\u201d murmured Nurse Jane,\nI never knew Uncle Wiggily to act\nlike this before! Something must\nbe the matter!\u201d\nBut Uncle Wiggily stayed in bed\nwith his eyes shut until, all of a\nsudden, he felt a hard pinch on\nhis left leg.\n\u201cDear me! I thought all the mos\nquitoes had gone dov/n south tor\nI the winter!\u201d exclaimed the rabbit,\nopening one eye. He looked around\nthe room but could see no mosquito,\nnor could he hear one buz/ /g. So\nhe went to sleep aguin and then, all\nof a sudden, he felt a pinch on ms\nSTEAD-D-DY!\nright leg. \"Another bite!\" exclaimed 1\nthe bunny.\nBut when he could see no buzzing\nbug he closed his eyes once more j\nbut opened them quickly when he\ntelt a pinch on ear and this time\nhe saw the edge of the bag under\nhis bed moving.\n\"Oh. my goodness!\" shouted the\nrabbit gentleman, hopping out of j\nbed. \u201cSome of the bad chaps have\ncome in and one of them is hiding j\nin the Christmas present bag. it\nmust bo the Fox. the Wolf or the\nBob Cat that reached out and\npinched me. Police Dog! Oh. Po\nlice Dog! Come here!\"\n\u201cWhat\u2019s the matter?\" asked Nurse;\nJane, who was sweeping the hall. j\n\"Get the Police Dog. quick!\" cried\nUncle Wiggily. hiding behind aj\nchair. \"There's a pinching bad chap\nin the Christmas bag!\"\nIn came the Police Dog with hts\ni big club. He looked all around the\ntabbit gentleman's bedroom and\nsaid:\n\"I don't see any bad chaps here.\n\"Look in the Chiistmas bag under\nmy bed!\" called Uncle Wiggily.\nAnd when the Police Dog looked.\nat the top of the bag he saw a jolly\ni clown doll who had on each hand a!\nshiny brass plate. And when tie\nPolice Dog punched the clown doll\nI in the middle, the jolly toy clapped\nhis hands and the brasses jingled I\nI musically.\n\"Where's the bad chap?\u201d asked,\nUncle Wiggily of the clown doll.\n\"There is no bad chap,\" was the\nanswer.\nI \"Then who pinched me?\" asked\nI Uncle Wiggily.\n\"I did!\" and the jolly clown doll\nI laughed. \"I thought you should be\nout of bed looking for adventures.\nUncle Wiggily. So I reached out of\nthe bag, and I clapped my brasse\ntogether, and I pinched you on the\nleft leg and on the right leg and on\nyour rear. Ha! Ha! Ha!\"\n\"Ha! Ha! Ha!\" laughed the Police\nDog. \"A pinching doll! Ha! Ha!\u201d\nThen the rabbit laughed and\neverybody was happy. The Christ-!\nmas bag was pushed back under the 1\ni bed, the pinching doll went to play\nj with the fire engine, and if the cho\ncolate drop will please try to stop\nlulling asleep when the lollypop\nwants to play tag. I'll tell you next\nabout Uncle Wiggily\u2019s tree present.\nCantaloupe Crop\n50,000 Acres\nAn estimate on the cantaloupe\nacreage for the coming season,\nbased on that already planted and\nthat which has been proposed, is\nmade by the agricultural commis-\nUoner\u2019s office as being in excess of\n50,000 acres. This compares favor\nable with last year\u2019s acreage, which\nwas approximately 52,000 acres.\nFigures for the acreage already\nplanted, given in round numbers,\nare as follows: brushed and cover\ned cantaloupes, 22,000; brushed and\ncovered honeydews, 4,000; brushed\nand covered honey balls, 1,500.\nAn exact statement of the acre\nQUICK CHRISTMAS\n7\nON YOUR\nAUTOMOBILE\nALSO CONTRACTS REFINANCED\nTruck Refinancing and Loans\nA Specialty\nSTERLING SECURITIES\nCOMPANY, Inc.\n674 Main FRED CROSS, Mgr. Phone 542\nEl Centro\nLooking Backward\nWhat the Prcs3 Files Tell of\nI Imperial Valley for this Date\nIn Tast Years\nTWENTY YEARS AGO\nDecember 13, 1910\nThe board of city trustees met\nin regular session last night with\nall the members present.\nTh.e resignation of Trustee W. O.\nHamilton was read and upon mo\ntion oi Foree was laid upon the\ntable until next meeting.\nPostmaster Miller wishes to in\nform the public that if they do\ntheir mailing for Christmas early\nthey will be able to have much\nbetter service than otherwise.\nFIFTEEN YEARS AGO\nDecember 15, 1915\nAn automobile party arriving in\nEl Centro last night included. Mr.\nand Mrs. F. L. Richards. Dr F. P.\nWhite, Herbert White and Hays L.\nLove, all residents of Lemon Grove.\nDr. White is looking for Imperial\nValley land with a view to buying\na ranch if he finds just what he\nwants.\nInterest in the charity ball to be\ngiven tonight at the Masonic Tem\nple by 12 El Centro girls to raise\nfunds for purchasing Christmas\ngifts for El Centro youngsters was\nindicated last night by the report\ned sale of many tickets.\nTEN YEARS AGO\nDecember 15, 1920\nThe Imperial Valley Camp of\nthe United Spanish War Veterans\nwill meet tonight in the county\ncourt house at 8 o'clock, and will\nelect officers for the coming year.\nAn offer was made yesterday to\nthe Irrigation District by the Mex\nican interests, through their\nspokesman, J. C. Allison of Calex\nico to submit to having their water\nrate raised from the present 87\ncents to sl.G(i, v.ith the proviso,\nhowever, that the Irrigation Dis\ntrict directors would permit a re\nision of their budget.\nMay Organize\nMilitia Here\ni Attempts to obtain a battalion\nof National Guard infantry for Im\nperial Valley were launched Friday\nnight at a meeting of the Reserve\nOfficers Association at the Barbara\nWorth hotel. El Centro, Calexico\nI and Brawley would be locations for\n1 the battalion.\nPrevious ,attempts to obtain a\nnational guard unit here have not\nI met with success but renewed ef\nforts will be made this year,\ni Officers were elected at last\nage will be given later :n the sea\nson by the office when the total\nacreage is planted.\nSpy Who Accuses\nGotham Police\nSensational charges that members\nof the New York police vice squad\nemployed him to \u201cframe\" vice\ncharges against women have been\nmade by Chile Mapocha Acuna,\nabove, alleged \u2018informer\" for the\npolice. Ills testimony In a court\ninvestigation collaborated that of\nfive women who told of being ar\nrested when no evidence had been\nobtained against them.\nnight\u2019s session as follows: Capt. S.\nG. Lefner, Brawley, president;\nSecond Lieut. A 1 G. Smith. El Cen\ntro, vice president; Second Lieut.\nHarney Archias, Brawley, secretary\nand treasurer; and Capt. C. P.\nDelp, council director.\nMap reading occupied the 20\nmen who attended the dinner and\nmeeting. The study was under the\ndirection of Capt. Lefner.\nTh.e next session of the associa\ntion is scheduled for the last Fri\nday in December.\nCALVIN G.\nMOITSSEAU\nFor Director Imperial Irrigation\nDistrict.\nlIIS PLATFORM:\nT hereby announce my candidacy for Director\nof the Imperial Irrigation District for El Centro-\nImperial division.\nAfter leaving school I spent four years with\nthe Southern Pacific Railroad in Oregon and y.itii\nthe Pacific Gas and Electric Company in Califor\nnia in construction work dealing with the con\nstruction of railroads, building a large dam on\nthe south fork of the Yuba River, installing hydro\nelectric plants, tunnels and waterways. 1 am 42\nyears of \u2022age. My hamily resides here and all ot\nmy interests are centered ir Imperial t ounty.\nIn presenting my candidacy I have the lollow\ning objects in view to be accomplished, and my\nplatform is as follows:\n1\u2014 I believe that the Delinquent Tar problem in Imperial\nCounty should receive careful consideration and this con\ndition he remedied by closer co-operation between the\nHoard of Supervisors of Imperial County and the Board of\nDirectors of the Imperial Irrigation District;\n2 frequent meetings between the Hoard of Directors and the\nBoard of Supervisors to discuss and remedy this and other\nsituations;\n:j_Th,. extending of drainage canals where drainage is need\ned, thereby assuring more favorable action on farm loans;\n4 \u2014The consolidation of the tax collecting and assessing de\npartments of county and district, thereby eliminating an\nitem of expense and making it more convenient for the\npeople. Although this cannot be accomplished for lour\nyears, now is the time to start it.\nr\u00bb\u2014Kull publicity through publication in a county newspaper of\nall proceedings of the Board of Directors and an itemized\naccount of all expenditures, although same is not required\nby law, and the present board has never caused it to he\ndune.\nI!\u2014If feasible, one engineering department for county anil dis\ntrict.\n7 American labor to be given preference on all Irrigation\nDistrict works.\n8\u2014 The expenditure of money derived from the sale of drain\nage bonds for drainage purposes only.\np decided curtailment in the expenditure of funds used foil\npublicity and other purposes.\n10\u2014Loyal support and the construction provided for in the\nSwing-Johnson and careful consideration of the prob\nlems it presents.\n31\u2014Decision to be made with the welfare of the entire com\nmunity uppermost in mind.\n12\u2014I believe that the tax rate can he lowered without effi\nciency being impaired.\n17\u2014I am a ranch owner and a taxpayer of Imperial County.\n14\u2014I have no conflicting outside interests.\nON THIS PLATFORM T SUBMIT MY CANDIDACY\nFOR YOUR CONSIDERATION\nCalvin G. Mousseau\nBHHBBBDSH \u25a0^'^gitatsgegsraHG\n3BGEs&\u00a323QI?\nRED CROSS THANKS\nTHOSE WHO AIDED\nFOOTBALL GAME\nThe El Centro committee of tbe\nAmerican Red Cross wishes to thank\npublicly all those who participated\nin and made possible the benefit\nfootball game on Friday, December\n12, between the Central Union high\nschool and the Central Union high\nschool alumni.\nIn addition to Ihe players on the\ntwo teams, special acknowledgement\nshould be made for the cooperation\nand assistance of Principal John L,\nHouse and Coach Robert Armstrong\nof the high schoo! faculty; also to\nErnest T. Sanders, who coached the\nalumni team, and to H. N. Hoskins\numpire; Jack Barnes, referee, and\nW. S. Hendry, head lineman, who\nofficated at the game; also to Dr,\nC. S. Brooks and Dr. L. C. House.\nWo wish also to express our ap\npreciation to the Imperial Valley\nPress for the publicity given.\nAmerican Rod Cross.\nEl Centro Branch\nBy Joe E. King, acting president.\nJ. W. Donohue.\nchairman finance committee.\nBIG DEER KILLED\nORR. Minn., (U.R)\u2014A 23)-pound\ndeer with 19-point antlers was shot\nnear here by M. J. Hoff on the\nopening day of the deer season, ft\nwas said to be the largest ever seen\nin this territory.\nHAVEKORST\nGUERNSEY FARMS\nNow have available Golden\nGuernsey Raw \u201cGuaranteed\nMilk\"\nPhone El Centro 546\nEARL VV. FITE\nPlumbing Shop\n1230 OLIVB\nPHONE 1047\n[broadway hotel\ni N. Broadway Los Angeles\n1 Opposite Hall of Beeords\n2,')0 Rooms. Refurnished all new. I\n$l.OO per day up.\nj SYDNEL SMITH. Prop. j","height":"29400","width":"23348"}}
